<Layout title="Rehabilitation & Stroke Recovery Assessment Tools" description="Rehabilitation and stroke recovery assessment tools used in nursing">
  <a href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/`} class="back-link">← Back to all categories</a>
  <div class="badge">Rehabilitation &amp; Stroke Recovery</div>
  <h1>Rehabilitation &amp; Stroke Recovery Assessment Tools</h1>
  <p>Tools for measuring motor recovery, functional outcomes, and quality of life after stroke and neurological injury.</p>

  <div class="tool-list">
    <h2>Assessment Tools</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Fugl-Meyer Assessment (FMA)</strong> — Comprehensive sensorimotor recovery assessment post-stroke. Motor subscale (upper/lower extremity), balance, sensation, and joint range/pain; widely used in stroke trials.</li>
      <li><strong>ARAT (Action Research Arm Test)</strong> — 19-item test of upper limb function using grasp, grip, pinch, and gross movement tasks. Scores 0–57; sensitive to improvement after stroke.</li>
      <li><strong>SIS (Stroke Impact Scale)</strong> — 59-item patient-reported outcome measure across 8 domains: strength, hand function, ADL/IADL, mobility, communication, emotion, memory/thinking, and participation.</li>
      <li><strong>NIHSS Serial Monitoring</strong> — Serial neurological examinations using the NIHSS to track stroke progression, improvement, or deterioration; guides acute treatment decisions and stroke unit management.</li>
      <li><strong>UPDRS Motor Subscale</strong> — Part III of the UPDRS specifically assessing Parkinson's disease motor manifestations including tremor, rigidity, bradykinesia, and postural instability.</li>
      <li><strong>DHI (Dizziness Handicap Inventory)</strong> — 25-item self-report questionnaire measuring vestibular disorder impact on physical, functional, and emotional aspects of daily life. Score 0–100.</li>
      <li><strong>ABC Scale (Activities-Specific Balance Confidence Scale)</strong> — 16-item self-report of balance confidence (0–100%) for specific activities. Predicts fall risk in community-dwelling older adults.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</Layout>
